 Duis aute irure dolor in reprehenderit in voluptate velit esse cillum dolore eu fugiat nulla pariatur.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,31),('<p>Mike Gee got the fright of his life when he returned home from gym just before dinner on Tue 24th&nbsp;Nov 2015.The 76 year old from Whangamata walked through to the family&rsquo;s living room at about 4.50pm. Alison, his wife and sweetheart of more than 50 years, was bending over Julian, their 42 year old son, who was unable to get up and unable to speak. Julian was in the throes of a severe seizure. Alison found him, after resting from recent hip surgery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Julian was diagnosed with Multiple Sclerosis on Anzac Day 2011 while living in Australia. He was 36 years old at the time.Mike and Alison are proud of the way their son has never let his condition get in the way of his love of fitness and exercise. Julian has faced many obstacles in life. Despite having suffered some neurological damage to his brain, he, like his Dad, has always kept in incredibly good shape.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To see Julian so incapacitated was a complete shock to Alison. She was relieved when Mike returned home. &ldquo;I made sure Julian wasn&rsquo;t swallowing his tongue, but I was pretty limited in what I could do,&rdquo; she recalls. Mike called 111. &ldquo;You could see the fear on Julian&rsquo;s face,&rdquo; Alison says, &ldquo;we were all scared.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They&rsquo;d never encountered anything like this before and wondered if he was having a stroke. &ldquo;He couldn&rsquo;t answer me, he&rsquo;d couldn&rsquo;t understand me and, then, he was gone,&rdquo; Mike says. &ldquo;He just had this look in his eyes,&rdquo; Alison says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>St John arrived in next to no time. &ldquo;They determined that the window of opportunity to help Julian was closing,&rdquo; says Mike, &ldquo;He had to be airlifted to hospital fast! Julian was loaded into the back of the ambulance and driven to the helicopter pad in the middle of town, to await the Westpac Rescue Helicopter&rsquo;s arrival.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,60),('<p>Mike and Alison followed by car. The family&rsquo;s GP and Senior Nurse had also arrived. &ldquo;They were all working on Julian in the ambulance when he had another full-on seizure,&rdquo; Mike says. Thanks to the quick-thinking and skill of all the medical professionals involved that day, including the Westpac 2 crew, who arrived in 28 minutes, Julian was stabilised and airlifted to Waikato Hospital.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;It was when he was airlifted away that it dawned on us just how serious his condition was,&rdquo; Mike says, &ldquo;I suddenly realised he could have died.&rdquo; Mike was charged with getting Alison home, who couldn&rsquo;t drive because of her hip operation. That&rsquo;s when she turned to him and said, in a few short words, &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t go without me!&rdquo; The couple were soon on their way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Julian would spend six nights in hospital. &ldquo;They did lumber punctures, MRIs, ultrasounds&hellip; they were so very thorough,&rdquo; Alison says, &ldquo;The diagnosis came back that it wasn&rsquo;t a stroke at all, but a seizure, a myoclonic seizure, related to his Multiple Sclerosis. They think exercise may have triggered it.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The doctors were impressed with Julian&rsquo;s excellent health. Julian&rsquo;s strength returned and he was soon pushing his Mum in her wheelchair around the hospital. &ldquo;I had to say, &lsquo;Stop it Julian&rsquo;&rdquo;, Alison laughs, &ldquo;&rsquo;Not so fast!&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With the proper medication, Julian&rsquo;s seizures haven&rsquo;t returned and he can continue enjoying his exercise. Julian is back to his fit and cheerful self. Julian proudly refers to everyone involved in his rescue as his &ldquo;life savers&rdquo;. &ldquo;They saved my life,&rdquo; he says.&nbsp;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,60),('<p>He was struggling to breathe.It was just after midnight on 24 November 2015 in Karioitahi, just outside of Waiuku, when Len started fighting for his life. &ldquo;I have experienced breathing difficulties before, but nothing like this,&rdquo; the 67 year old father, grandfather, and great grandfather recalls.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Len managed to give his wife Rawinia a gentle nudge.&ldquo;I couldn&rsquo;t even get up,&rdquo; he says.&ldquo;You couldn&rsquo;t even talk,&rdquo; Rawinia says, &ldquo;You were gasping for air. I&rsquo;d seen him like this before, but it was never this bad.&rdquo;Rawinia called the ambulance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Len remembers first responders, emergency partner St John, getting to their rural property fast and giving him something to help with his breathing. He doesn&rsquo;t recall much after that.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is where Rawinia helps fill in the gaps.&ldquo;Len wasn&rsquo;t very well at all. If the ambulance crew were to drive Len to hospital, there was a chance we might lose him. That&rsquo;s when the helicopter was called in and it came very quickly too,&rdquo; she says.Westpac 2 landed in a paddock, on the other side of the road, adjacent to the family home.&ldquo;We were lucky there weren&rsquo;t any cattle in there!&rdquo; Rawinia laughs.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,61),('<p>&ldquo;The crew were amazing. It was very dark and they had to calm me down too,&rdquo; she says, &ldquo;I was a bit frightened about going in the helicopter. It was my first time!&rdquo;Len and Rawinia were transported to Auckland Hospital in just 19 minutes from take-off. &ldquo;Without the assistance of the crew, I think I would have been in dire straights,&rdquo; Len says.&ldquo;That&rsquo;s quite true,&rdquo; Rawinia says, &ldquo;I think we would have lost him if they weren&rsquo;t there.&rdquo;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When Len awoke the following day, the doctors were very surprised to see he&rsquo;d pulled through.&ldquo;They were amazed at how quick the recovery was, considering the condition I was in,&rdquo; he says, &ldquo;It was a blessing. A real miracle!&rdquo;. Len was in critical care for five days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So shocking was the incident, Len and Rawinia have moved into Waiuku town.The family are very grateful that the Westpac Rescue Helicopter was able to come to their aid.&ldquo;I would like to thank them all from the bottom of my heart for all the effort they put in to saving my life,&rdquo; Len says.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,61),('<p>The Macleans are a young, tight-knit family of four from Warkworth.As we juggle our interview with two active boys in tow, Jack (5 years) and Finn (3 years), Jade (Mum) and Sam (Dad) are a well-oiled machine.While one parent focuses on what&rsquo;s being asked, the other is knee deep in building blocks. When it&rsquo;s time to swap places, the other already has a story book in hand.Sadly, one thing, they all have in common is asthma. At one time or another, this debilitating condition has affected each of them.Asthma and two young boys, with energy to burn, don&rsquo;t mix very well. Finn developed his breathing difficulties when he got bronchiolitis at just six months of age.&ldquo;Ever since, his colds have gone straight to his lungs,&rdquo; Jade says, &ldquo;but it&rsquo;s when our boys aren&rsquo;t active, that&rsquo;s when we know something&rsquo;s very wrong.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nothing could have prepared the family for what happened on 24th&nbsp;November 2015.Finn was ill during the night. Jade watched over her son in the small hours, while Sam took up the next shift.&nbsp; &ldquo;I could see Jade had Finn sitting up in his bean bag to help with his breathing,&rdquo; Sam recalls, &ldquo;Finn is naturally a very pale boy, but, to me, he looked really pale and he was lethargic too.&rdquo;&ldquo;Sam was worried and woke me up,&rdquo; says Jade, &ldquo;We noticed Finn had gone a bit blue under his bottom lip. We knew that wasn&rsquo;t good, so I said, &lsquo;OK, it&rsquo;s time to call the ambulance.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;The ambulance arrived in no time at all. They took one look at him and said, &lsquo;This is a serious condition. We&rsquo;ve got to get him to hospital right now!&rsquo;&rdquo;. While ambulance staff supplied Finn with vital oxygen, they determined that, because it was peak hour traffic time on the northern motorway, the rescue helicopter was needed to get the toddler to hospital fast.&rdquo; In 14 minutes, the Auckland Westpac Rescue Helicopter had touched down in a reserve opposite where the family lived. It took just 13 minutes to get Finn to Starship Hospital.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,63),('<p>&ldquo;I think that getting Finn there quickly was the big difference between it going well and going south,&rdquo; Jade says, trying to hold back tears. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s really sad to think had they not been here Finn might not be here today. We&rsquo;re just really, really grateful Sam, aren&rsquo;t we?&rdquo;. &ldquo;Yeah,&rdquo; Sam replies, putting his free arm around his wife. &ldquo;When it comes to children&rsquo;s respiratory problems you either go to Waitakere or Starship Hospital &ndash; it&rsquo;s not just a trip to North Shore Hospital. You&rsquo;ve have to go that much further.&nbsp; Having a rescue helicopter is just like having insurance. You may not ever need it, but if something happens, it&rsquo;s great to know it&rsquo;s there.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finn remained in a critical condition during the flight and was in Starship&rsquo;s Intensive Care Unit for three nights. &ldquo;They were exercising every life-saving asthma protocol you could think of,&rdquo; Jade recalls, &ldquo;It was really, really serious.&rdquo; Finn was readmitted one more night, earlier this year, for further observation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;If things go downhill, they go down fast,&rdquo; Jade says, &ldquo;One moment he could be coughing a bit and then half an hour later, we could be calling an ambulance.&rdquo; Almost one year on from the incident, Finn and the family are doing well. Despite the uncertainty surrounding the boy&rsquo;s health, the family are determined they will continue to lead active and healthy lives.&ldquo;One thing&rsquo;s for sure,&rdquo; says Sam, &ldquo;If it wasn&rsquo;t for the helicopter being there that day, our lives would be a lot different today.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,63),('<p>Anniversary Weekend 2015 is one Stewart and Pauline Rundle won&rsquo;t forget.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>26 January 2015 was the day Stewart fell 30 metres down a cliff.&nbsp;The father of two children, two grandchildren and two great grandchildren, the former school Principal has lived a full and active life with loads of stories to tell. When you meet Stewart, it&rsquo;s hard to believe he&rsquo;s 86 years old. While he&rsquo;s successfully defied age, unfortunately that day he wasn&rsquo;t able to defy gravity. The fact that he was in good shape, and with a sharp mind, would certainly factor into Stewart defying death.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An avid adventurer and explorer, Stewart was well aware of the dangers of owning a clifftop residence. He always kept his distance from the edge and made sure he only stood on ground that he had seen the builders stand on. Unfortunately, Stewart wasn&rsquo;t expecting it to give way underneath him though!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He says his only thought, on the way down, was, &ldquo;How do I survive this?&rdquo; Recalling his climbing knowledge, Stewart did his best to position his body, so that when he impacted, his back wouldn&rsquo;t break from the force. Spread-eagled like a cat and turning onto his stomach, his only thought was to stay alive. &nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unfortunately Stewart collided with the cliff several times on his way down.&nbsp;&ldquo;I heard things going with every bounce,&rdquo; he grimly recalls. Stewart saw an opportunity to grab a passing shrub in a last ditch effort to save himself, only to have it slip through his fingers. He didn&rsquo;t know it at the time, but he&rsquo;d broken his gripping arm, and was unable to hold on.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the last ten metres, Stewart went into free-fall and landed onto the basalt rocks below. Shipped in many years ago to stop the sea eroding the cliffs, they did nothing to cushion Stewart&rsquo;s fall and he ended up with his head above the waves which were breaking around him, his left shoulder wedged tightly between two rocks. The pain was intense. Every time he tried to move, he would pass out.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Men half his age would have died instantly. Emergency services would later say it was Stewart&rsquo;s good health and fitness that saved him &ndash; that and the cellphone in his back left pocket (which he normally wouldn&rsquo;t put there) were crucial to his survival. The trouble was, with his left arm out of action, he had no chance of reaching his phone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stewart would lie there for three and a half hours. Any golden hour opportunity had long gone. (Patients typically need medical care within the first hour of an accident or their long-term chances of a full recovery or survival significantly reduce). To keep his mind busy, Stewart whispered affirmations to himself. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m going to make it,&rdquo; he repeatedly said. He recalled the three Bs of first aid &ndash; Breathing, Beating (Heart) and Bleeding. He would routinely run his free right hand over his body to check for profusely wet patches of blood. So far, so good.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the meantime, Pauline was desperate to know where Stewart was and phoned him again and again. He didn&rsquo;t pick up. It never occurred to her that her extra cautious husband had gone over the cliff.&nbsp;Despite it being wet, Stewart&rsquo;s cellphone kept ringing. Stewart nervously listened, anxious that the battery life of his cellphone, his only lifeline, would run out.&nbsp;Fortunately for Stewart, the tide was on its way out too but he realised he was bitterly cold.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was the first time he thought, &ldquo;I could die here.&rdquo; It dawned on him that the only way to get out of this situation, was to get himself out.&nbsp;Stewart decided that the best way to do this, and to take his mind off the pain, was to scream. He gave it all he had. His screams were high but soft. Six of his ribs were broken, it&rsquo;s all he could muster up. No one could have heard him but it was just the distraction he needed to get himself out. With every agonising breath, he freed his broken body. Before he knew it, he was out.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,64),('<p>Now Stewart had to act fast. With his right arm he loosened his belt, dropped his pants, and pulled his left back pocket around to position the phone within reach of his good right arm. Once free, he managed to put a call in to 111, requesting all four emergency services &ndash; the fire department to get down to him, the ambulance to deliver first aid, the helicopter to get him out, and the police to coordinate it all. The emergency operator said later it was the first time a Status One patient had helped coordinate their own rescue!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stewart was starting to lose consciousness again. He remembered seeing a red kayak heading towards him, thinking it was strange it was going towards the rocks. A &ldquo;big burly man&rdquo; (a policeman who was first on the scene) got out and held Stewart&rsquo;s hand. Stewart found this very comforting and calming.&ldquo;I am going to make it,&rdquo; Stewart whispered before passing out. When Stewart came to, in the Emergency Department at Auckland Hospital, his first words were exactly the same, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m going to make it,&rdquo; he said.&nbsp;By his side was Pauline who answered, &ldquo;Yes, of course you are.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Auckland Rescue Helicopter got to Stewart in just four minutes from take-off. Pilot/Training Manager Paul Robinson recalls Stewart&rsquo;s rescue being very challenging. &ldquo;The hoist used to winch Stewart up was on the right side of the aircraft meaning that the position I needed to be in caused the wind to be behind me,&rdquo; he says, &ldquo;Not ideal, but we had no other option. I was careful not to get too close to the cliff, as this might dislodge debris, sending it tumbling down towards Stewart or, even more catastrophic, towards our spinning rotors.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once they were safely hovering, Crewman Ati Wynyard winched Intensive Care Flight Paramedic, Russell &ldquo;Rusty&rdquo; Clark, down by cable, to the scene below. Rusty then assessed Stewart and confirmed a winch up was the safest option. After getting Stewart onto a stretcher, with the help of local ambulance and fire crews, Rusty and Stewart were lifted aboard. Also onboard to assist was HEMS (Helicopter Emergency Medical Specialist) doctor, Chris Denny. Being the only civilian helicopter service to carry HEMS doctors on board, Chris could help Rusty deliver life-saving aid straight away. Without a doubt, this expert care helped save Stewart&rsquo;s life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once stabilised Stewart was flown to Auckland Hospital&rsquo;s critical care unit. He was there for three days. Stewart had suffered five breaks to his back (but, thankfully, not his spine) and three in his neck, as well as a broken right arm, shoulder and ribs. Stewart says that if the Westpac Rescue Helicopter hadn&rsquo;t been there to winch him to safety, rescue services would have had a lot of trouble, and spent a lot of time, trying to get him out either by hoisting him up the cliff or by sea.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I wouldn&rsquo;t have made it,&rdquo; he says. We think he is very brave, but Stewart doesn&rsquo;t agree. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m not brave. What I did was self-preservation,&rdquo; he tells us. &ldquo;Very brave people are those who do these things on a daily basis; those who take calculated risks for others.&rdquo; And that&rsquo;s how he views all those involved in his rescue. He was later told by the crew that it was quite a tricky rescue. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s bravery,&rdquo; he says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stewart&rsquo;s rehabilitation is ongoing since his accident. His left arm may never fully recover. He still has a hard time picking things up, but he hasn&rsquo;t let the fear of his accident get the better of him. His sunny outlook on life remains.&nbsp;When Stewart finds the recovery process somewhat demanding his favourite affirmation is, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m a very lucky man.&rdquo; By the time he has repeated it several times he is feeling much better.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stewart remains an avid supporter of our service and is leaving a gift in his Will to the Auckland Rescue Helicopter Trust. He wants to ensure that the service remains available to those who may need it and we are very grateful for this support.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,64),('<p>Waiheke&rsquo;s Matty and Jane Macdonald were excited about daughter Nixie&rsquo;s arrival into the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The young couple had opted for a home birth for their first born. Unfortunately no one read the memo that Nixie was on &ldquo;island time&rdquo;. As the hours ticked by, time started to work against mother and daughter. &ldquo;Nixie and I were doing great at first,&rdquo; Jane recalls, &ldquo;She was two weeks overdue, but on her way. Early Sunday morning I experienced my first contraction and became fully dilated. As Sunday turned to Monday, I began the pushing stage but, despite my best efforts, and incredible support of Matty and my midwife, Nixie was quite happy to stay put!&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After several hours of pushing, Jane was able to encourage Nixie further down and a second midwife was called in. &ldquo;We were hopeful our little girl would be with us shortly and I remember&nbsp;Matty&nbsp;saying, &ldquo;I can see her head&rdquo; but Nixie wouldn&rsquo;t budge!&rdquo; Jane&rsquo;s excitement turned to exhaustion. All she cared about now was ensuring Nixie was healthy and safe. The Auckland Westpac Rescue Helicopter was called in to help.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,66),('<p>&ldquo;I felt that, if we made it to the helicopter, then everything would be OK.&rdquo;<br />\r\nJane was flown to Auckland Hospital&rsquo;s birthing unit in just 10 minutes from takeoff. &ldquo;When we were hooked up to the CTG monitor, we realised Nixie was showing signs of distress. Later, when we held our little girl, it really sunk in that without the help of the rescue helicopter service, things could have turned out quite differently. The level of appreciation that goes along with this realisation is difficult to put into words.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe Macdonald family are doing well. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s amazing watching Nixie grow and develop each day. We feel like we&rsquo;re the luckiest parents on earth.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,66),('<p>Nole was enjoying a day out on the water, fishing off his jet ski. He certainly wasn&rsquo;t looking for trouble, (he was fit and felt good for his age). Trouble unfortunately found him!&nbsp; Nole, out of the blue, experienced severe back pain. He didn&rsquo;t know it at the time, but he was having a heart attack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just north of Tairua, some 3km off shore, Nole&rsquo;s immediate thoughts were to make it back to dry land and to Judy, his wife of 40 years. When Nole walked through the door of their holiday home, Judy put in an urgent 111 call &ndash; a call that would save his life. Emergency partner St John rushed Nole to Thames Hospital where he was stabilised.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While the Auckland &amp; Coromandel Westpac Rescue Helicopter was very busy that day, Nole was relieved to hear he could be emergency transfered to Auckland Hospital&rsquo;s Cardiology Unit.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,67),('<p>&ldquo;Their arrival was so welcome,&rdquo; he says, &ldquo;I knew I was in the hands of professionals who knew exactly what they were doing.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The couple recognised some of the crews&rsquo; faces from the Code:1 TV show. Not wanting to take away from their professionalism, Nole credits their good humour as being a big help during his ordeal and in helping Judy cope with the shock as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nole would like to encourage you to give generously to this Annual Appeal. &ldquo;I hope I never have need of the service again, so that my donation will help the next person,&rdquo; Nole tells us, &ldquo;I will continue giving to the service and I hope you will too.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,67),('<p>Braden&rsquo;s future was mapped out. He was looking forward to joining the navy. Going for a run one sunny evening, he didn&rsquo;t notice the car behind him. The driver experienced some sun strike and drove straight into Braden.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In just seconds, Braden&rsquo;s world had changed. He suffered two breaks to his lower left leg, a graze to his left arm, and a cut to his forehead where he hit the car&rsquo;s windscreen. Braden didn&rsquo;t panic. He said he, &ldquo;felt calm.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was focusing on what had happened and what would be best for me to do in this situation,&rdquo; he says, &ldquo;It wasn&rsquo;t until later that I thought about my family, especially my mother. I was concerned about what she would be thinking, feeling. Mum encouraged me to apply for the navy and I knew this probably wouldn&rsquo;t happen now.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thames locals, including St John, rallied to Braden&rsquo;s side. When the Westpac Rescue Helicopter arrived, Braden says he was feeling the effects of the morphine. &ldquo;I can remember a low humming noise and asking everyone why they were wearing helmets.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,69),('<p>Braden was flown to Waikato Hospital - a quick 23 minute flight away. Two months on, Braden says he&rsquo;s looking forward to running again. &ldquo;Just the simple fact that I will be able to run makes me enjoy the thought of it so much more,&rdquo; he says. He has also had time to rethink his future and is now looking forward to studying architecture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apart from saving lives, Braden says rescue helicopter donors should look at &ldquo;the bigger picture&rdquo;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Accidents affect more than the person involved &ndash; my family, the people in the car and their family, my partner and her family, and the people who came to help me were all involved in some way. The Westpac Rescue Helicopter not only saves lives, it often saves others from heartache as well.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,69),('<p>Mirte was enjoying watching daughter Nikita ride her horse &ldquo;Rocket&rdquo;. The thought of Mirte taking a helmet for herself, hadn&rsquo;t crossed her mind.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As mum and daughter walked home, family dog &quot;Opal&quot; went into the bushes to investigate something. Mirte doesn&rsquo;t remember much about what happened next. This is where Nikita helps &lsquo;fill in the gaps&rsquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unaware that Opal had disappeared, Rocket got a fright when the dog jumped out of the bushes. Rocket shied sideways, knocking Mirte over. Rocket then turned and ran home, stepping on Mirte&rsquo;s head in the process. With Mirte having just sustained a major head injury, Nikita had to act fast. Terrified for her mother, she flagged down a passing car who dialled 111.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Severely concussed, Mirte remembers little but worrying about her daughter. &ldquo;Nikita said I kept trying to reassure her and hold her hand,&rdquo; Mirte says, &ldquo;When the rescue crew came, they had trouble separating us. Once I had my faculties back, I realised how incredibly lucky I was not to have been killed by the blow and that the Westpac Rescue Helicopter was there to get me quickly to Auckland Hospital where all the brain injury specialists are.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,70),('<p>&ldquo;I was also very grateful that the crew could be there for Nikita when I couldn&rsquo;t be,&rdquo; she says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the long road to recovery, Mirte has a greater appreciation of the time she spends with her family. She is no longer able to ride because doing so would make her injury worse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;ve had to come to terms with the fact that my life is more important than my passion for riding. I put more energy into Nikita&rsquo;s riding pursuits now.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m just so glad you&rsquo;re alive,&rdquo; Nikita adds, &ldquo;I think we both are aren&rsquo;t we?&rdquo; Mum warmly replies.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,70),('<p>Sapphire was doing what a lot of Kiwi kids love to do.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She was climbing a tree. Unfortunately for Sapphire, the branch she stood on snapped. Three metres above the ground, Sapphire fell and landed heavily on her head and neck. Luckily the spritely girl from Wellsford wasn&rsquo;t knocked out by the impact, but she did suffer some concussion. Best friend Kayleigh, not far away, ran to Sapphire&rsquo;s side and asked if she was OK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sapphire says she thought it was all a dream. &ldquo;It was like I was seeing it all in slow motion,&rdquo; she says, &ldquo;Like I was watching a video.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sapphire patiently lay under the tree waiting for help to come. Not easy to do when you&rsquo;re 10 years old and active! When Sapphire heard the Westpac Rescue Helicopter was coming she said she felt happy, because she knew they would &ldquo;get her to hospital fast.&rdquo; As she lay under the tree, she watched the Westpac Rescue Helicopter fly overhead.&nbsp;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,71),('<p>It took the rescue crew just 22 minutes to get to Sapphire. Sapphire sported a big welt on the left hand side of her forehead, a laceration inside her mouth and a swollen top left lip, but thankfully she was alert, in good colour and could move all her limbs. Experiencing pain in her right shoulder and spine, she was fitted with a c-spine to help stabilise her neck.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It took just 20 minutes from take off to transport Sapphire to Starship Childrens Hospital. Sapphire is now on the mend. She still wears a neck brace, to enable two torn ligaments in her neck to heal, but thankfully, there are no fractures to her neck.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A girl of few words but with the biggest smile, Sapphire, says &ldquo;Thank You&rdquo; to all the donors who helped her that day.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,71),('<p>Less than 24 hours after Rory &amp; his sweetheart said &ldquo;I do&rdquo;, disaster struck.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rory would fall head over heels again. Only this time, there was no fairy tale ending for Rory and his partner of seven years, Karen (&quot;Kaz&quot;).<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe young couple had just returned to New Zealand from a three year OE to be wed at the family bach in Matarangi. Spending some time in Nicaragua, Kaz took up surfing lessons. On reflection, after what happened the day after their big event, Kaz jokes, &ldquo;Rory should have taken lessons too!&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOn 29th November 2015, the new groom decided to catch some early waves with his cousin while Kaz popped into town to run some errands. Rory went to stand up on his surfboard but it slipped out from under him. Falling headfirst onto the seabed below, he heard a big &ldquo;crunch&rdquo; but managed to get himself up again. Rory immediately felt pains running up and down his right arm. &ldquo;At first I thought I was having a heart attack,&rdquo; he says, &ldquo;Then I realised it was the wrong arm for this to happen.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,72),('<p>Despite Rory&rsquo;s accident he was incredibly lucky that day. His uncle, a back surgeon along with two cousins, also back surgeons, identified a severe neck break and a risk of tetraplegia. They called for the Westpac Rescue Helicopter. Kaz returned to find Rory, ashen faced, lying on his bed, surrounded by family, and the Westpac Rescue Helicopter on the way to help. An emergency helicopter ride, for her and Rory, had replaced the plan for the &lsquo;day after&rsquo; lunch party.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nRory was flown with great care to Middlemore Hospital to get the specialist help he needed. Rory suffered a severe neck break. &ldquo;He was 2mm from becoming a tetraplegic&rdquo;, his uncle says. &ldquo;Travelling the windy roads to get help would have been disastrous,&rdquo; Rory says, &ldquo;I am very grateful the Westpac Rescue Helicopter could be there for me that day.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,72),('<p>It was an early start for Gracie and her family from Kennedy Bay on Friday 26th June.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the small hours of the morning, Gracie was running a fever and her breathing was raspy and laboured. &ldquo;Sickness is frightening when you don&rsquo;t know what you&rsquo;re dealing with,&rdquo; Mum Conor says, &ldquo;We contacted an afterhours clinic and found out she had croup (a viral illness in young children which causes narrowing of the upper airways).&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs the night wore on, Gracie&rsquo;s condition took a turn for the worse. &ldquo;Gracie just wasn&rsquo;t coping with the virus and high temperatures,&rdquo; Conor recalls, &ldquo;She had a febrile convulsion (a seizure caused by the body overheating). Having seen this once before, we knew what to do. We put her in a cold shower to cool her down.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nKeeping a watchful eye over their daughter, the family arranged an early visit to their GP - a good half hour away. &ldquo;That day there was a tangi on that I hoped to attend. I held off to see our GP first but the nurse asked if we could come back in 20 minutes. Gracie still wasn&rsquo;t very well but, to look at her, we thought she was on the mend. I popped across to pay my respects but, as soon as I opened the car door she had a seizure again. This one was very intense. Gracie was foaming at the mouth and I just starting yelling for help.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAs luck would have it, the tangi was held at the local fire station. &ldquo;As I carried her in my arms, the town&rsquo;s emergency and medical people came running.&rdquo; Gracie&rsquo;s body trembled as the St John Ambulance crew assessed her. At times she stopped breathing. &ldquo;Doctors said her seizure lasted a full eight minutes. The Westpac Rescue Helicopter crew were tasked to meet us at the town&rsquo;s airstrip. The thing I appreciated most was knowing they were coming. I felt a weight lift from my shoulders, knowing we were in the right hands and would get to hospital in time.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,73),('<p>In just 25 minutes the Westpac Rescue Helicopter arrived from its Auckland City base. HEMS Medical Director Chris Denny was on duty that day. &ldquo;I could see Gracie was scared and finding it difficult to breathe,&rdquo; Chris recalls, &ldquo;but she was alert, having received such excellent care from the local GP as well as the team from St John Ambulance. Because we&rsquo;re in Coromandel often, we know most of these people on a first name basis. Having dealt with illness and injury together, we could continue working at a very good pace.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDad Gerry, in his bee suit (work clothes), arrived just in time to kiss Mum and daughter goodbye before they took off. As a Dad himself, Chris knows how important it was to be there for the family too. &ldquo;This is a very remote setting and Gracie&rsquo;s family already had a lot to deal with that day,&rdquo; he says, &ldquo;Intensive Care Flight Paramedic Marcel Driessen and I did our best to let them know how Gracie was doing and to reassure them that everything was under control.&rdquo;<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn just 37 minutes, Gracie arrived at Waikato Hospital in a much improved state and was discharged the following morning. Fighting off tears, Conor struggles to convey what it meant having the community and the Auckland &amp; Coromandel Westpac Rescue Helicopter there for Gracie when she needed them the most.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s when young Billy speaks for his Mum. &ldquo;They saved my little sister&rsquo;s life!&rdquo; he says.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,73),('<p>&quot;I was falling in and out of consciousness when I heard the sound of those rotors&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the 23rd of February 2013, 14 year old Finley Savage slipped and fell 15 metres down a cliff face while going for a walk with a mate on Grant Island, Mahurangi. He had multiple head and arm injuries as well as a broken femur. As they had no cell phone with them, his mate Robbie had to go for help.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I was lying there on my own in heaps of pain thinking that the only way I&rsquo;m going to get out of here is if Robbie can get the rescue helicopter to come and find me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I was falling in and out of consciousness when I heard the sound of those rotors. Best sound I&rsquo;ve ever heard.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,74),('<p>I was falling in and out of consciousness when I heard the sound of those rotors. Best sound I&rsquo;ve ever heard.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finley has recovered well from his ordeal and gives thanks to the rescue crew for being there when he really needed them. &ldquo;Those guys are pretty amazing. One minute I&rsquo;m getting winched off the beach and the next thing I know I&rsquo;m in Auckland Hospital.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finley and his family urge you to continue to help the chopper. &ldquo;After the accident my mum said how lucky we were that the helicopter was there, because we never thought we&rsquo;d ever need them. If you can help them help others then please do so.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,74),('<p>On the 16th of October 2012, two month old baby Troy took a turn for the worse, experiencing severe breathing difficulties. His condition was getting steadily worse so the Westpac Rescue Helicopter was called. Troy&rsquo;s mum Carol was facing every parents worst nightmare.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Troy&rsquo;s breathing was getting worse and he seemed for some unknown reason to be choking. We just grabbed him and went searching for the local ambulance. Once we got to St Johns they reassured me that things would be ok and when I saw the rescue helicopter coming in, I felt even more reassured.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It turned out that young Troy&rsquo;s problems were caused by a previously undetected allergy to the milk formula that he had taken. Today he is a happy and healthy 10 month old boy.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,76),('<p>&ldquo;One of our deciding factors in coming to a rural community to live, is knowing that we have great local emergency services and that in dire situations we can rely upon our own rescue helicopters. The rescue crew are just amazing.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Troy&rsquo;s rescue was one of almost 800 missions carried out by your rescue helicopter crews last year and this simply would not have been possible without your help.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;d really like to thank all of you who have helped the rescue helicopters in the past and I urge you to help them again this year, so they can continue to help more families like ours.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank You</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,76),('<p>On the 1st of October 2012, 8 year old John Schouten was hit by a car at high speed, suffering multiple injuries. The Westpac Rescue Helicopter quickly responded to the accident. John&rsquo;s mum, Connie, is very thankful that we have such a highly skilled rescue service in the Auckland region.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;It&rsquo;s every parents worst nightmare and it certainly was for me when John got bowled over. To see the Westpac Rescue Helicopter team working on my boy, all I could do was hold out hope.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,78),('<p>Dr Chris and the crew were amazing, putting me at ease whilst providing our son with the best possible care. My family are so pleased that they were there to help us when we really needed them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I urge you to support the rescue helicopter in any way that you can, so that they can help other families like ours.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,78),('<p>On the 8th December 2012, 3 year old Quinn was found unconscious and not breathing on the bottom of a public swimming pool.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Quinns mother Sarena is full of praise for those that came to Quinn&rsquo;s aid that day. &ldquo;If not for the quick reaction of a fellow swimmer, who revived Quinn, and the fast response time of the rescue helicopter things could have been quite different for my family&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;The lady who attended to Quinn was amazing and the sight of the Westpac Rescue Helicopter coming in to get my boy out of there as quickly as possible really brought it home to me just how lucky we are to have such incredible emergency services&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,82),('<p>&ldquo;We are quite isolated where we live in Kaukapakapa and the rescue helicopter and crew provide us all with the peace of mind in knowing that help is never far away&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4><strong>&ldquo;I urge you to help the rescue helicopter in anyway you can, allowing the crew to get to their next patient as quickly as possible&rdquo;.</strong></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>Quinns rescue was one of 785 attended to by your rescue helicopter last year.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,82),('<p>Westpac Rescue Helicopter Advanced Paramedic Chris Deacon has been working out of the back of your rescue helicopter for 18 years - he has you to thank for the many experiences that he&rsquo;s had over that time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;In the 18 years I&rsquo;ve been flying I&rsquo;ve become acutely aware that it&rsquo;s all about teamwork. Whether it be reviving the lady of whom a dolphin has landed on top of, or being winched into the Hunuas to extract a tramper of who&rsquo;s suffered a heart attack, it&rsquo;s team work that gets our patient to the care they often desperately need.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,83),('<p>&ldquo;Something that I&rsquo;ve always been aware of is that the teamwork doesn&rsquo;t just involve the helicopter but rather it starts with you. If you weren&rsquo;t supporting us we wouldn&rsquo;t be flying very far, so I need to thank you for being part of our team&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chris and his fellow crew were involved in close to 800 rescue missions last year, half of which were fully funded by you, our supporters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chris and his team need your backing again this year.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,83),('<p>Hibiscus Coast resident and early childhood teacher Jenny Fox-Shakespeare fell badly when tramping up Rangitoto Island on the 3rd of February this year, breaking her leg and badly damaging<br />\r\nher ankle.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;There was no where the helicopter could land so Paramedic Russell Clarke came down the narrow path to winch me on board. I was very impressed by the gentle way I was safely taken through the trees to the helicopter hovering above.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I never, for a moment, thought that I&rsquo;d ever find myself being winched on board our rescue helicopter but I&rsquo;m so very pleased that those guys and girls that fly on the chopper are there for us all.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,84),('<p>Jenny&rsquo;s rescue was one of 250 that the rescue helicopter crews have performed already this year and they really need your financial backing to continue the work that they do.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I&rsquo;m so grateful for their help. I have always admired the dedication, skill and bravery of the Westpac Rescue Helicopter team. They are so humble about what they do&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;I urge you to think how you would also be incredibly grateful to have their help if you or one of your children or grandchildren ever needed them.&quot;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,84),('<p>By sharing your story about your rescue, you can help us keep our service top of mind and help educate our community about the vital work we do.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Positive media can have the same effect as a monetary donation. Increased awareness can ultimately lead to increased fundraising.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,114),('<p>If you have a story you are happy to share with the media and/ or our supporters, please contact:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kerrie Spicer</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Communications Advisor</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Phone: (09) 950 7222 or <a href=\"mailto:kerrie@arht.org.nz?subject=My%20Story&amp;body=The%20time%20I%20needed%20the%20rescue%20helicopter%20was\">email </a><a href=\"mailto:kerrie@arht.org.nz?subject=My%20story&amp;body=My%20story%20took%20place%20on%20\">Kerrie</a>.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,114),('<p>One of the ways you can help your Auckland &amp; Coromandel Westpac Rescue Helicopters is by donating your time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are many ways you can support us a volunteer. Here are just a few examples: shaking a bucket and collecting donations, merchandise selling, sausage sizzling, raffle minding, drink serving, and attending to parking at fundraising events.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,118),('<p>Some of the events volunteers have helped us with in the past include: The Easter Show, the Man O&#39;War Summer Lunch on Waiheke Island, BMW Polo Event and at Open Days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you would like to volunteer, please complete the following form.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,118),('<p>Is it possible to save a life and get fit at the same time?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>YES!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Rescue Run&nbsp;presented by Cisco will take place on November 19th at Woodhill Forest and will involve teams of six negotiating their way through simulated earthquakes, floods and car pile-ups!&nbsp;Most importantly, your inclusion will help fund the operation of the Auckland based Westpac Rescue Helicopters. We need 100 teams to train up and raise $5000 each for the chopper. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why? Because there&rsquo;s never been a better time to save a life!&nbsp;WE CAN BE HEROES!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/WCF0W490BBA\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Get some teammates together from your friends or workmates, and use this amaznig opportunity to get fit in support of a great cause. When you register you will receive dedicated fundraising support as well as a training guide to make sure you are prepared for the big day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the day you&#39;ll experience an event like no other before it in NZ or the rest of the world. Your fitness and mental strength will be tested, just like the rescue helicopter crew&#39;s are tested every day. Alongside simulated natural disasters we will have mental challenges put together by other important emergency services, giving you a truly unique event experience and some insight into the important lives of our emergency service heroes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For more information or to register visit&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.rescuerun.org.nz\">www.rescuerun.org.nz</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Or find us on Facebook, Twitter and Instagram by searching for @NZRescueRun.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have any more questions don&#39;t hesitate to contact us directly. Our events coordinator Katie would love to hear from you: events@arht.org.nz</p>','col-xs-12',0,1,138),('<p>ARHT FUND RAISERLorem&nbsp;ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco laboris consequat.Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco laboris consequat.Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco laboris consequat.Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco laboris consequat.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,139),('<p>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco laboris consequat.Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco laboris consequat.Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco laboris consequat.Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit, sed do eiusmod tempor incididunt ut labore et dolore magna aliqua. Ut enim ad minim veniam, quis nostrud exercitation ullamco laboris consequat.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,139),('<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/ambassadors/pippa.jpg\" style=\"width: 60px; height: 90px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>You&rsquo;ve seen her on the telly, most recently as presenter for Fair-Go and defender of Kiwis who have been left with very little options.&nbsp; Pippa Wetzell is a welcome addition to many of our homes, at least once a week, and she often does the odd stint on Seven Sharp and Breakfast too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pippa started working at TVNZ, one of our Corporate Sponsors, in the 90s, straight out of a Communications Degree. Working the overnight shift on the news desk, Pippa&rsquo;s roles included reporting and producing for Breakfast, Midday News, and Business. She was also a reporter for ONE News for five years, before taking up the presenting role on Breakfast.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A busy mum as well, we are very fortunate to have Pippa on board as our Ambassador, flying the flag for her local Westpac Rescue Helicopter Service on top of her everyday life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pippa tells us that supporting the service is an easy choice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;There are so many wonderful stories of people whose lives have been saved because of the Auckland and Coromandel Westpac Rescue Helicopter Service,&rdquo; she says, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m born and bred in Auckland and we holiday regularly in the Coromandel too. My family has spent a lot of time out and about exploring these beautiful regions and appreciate the incredible service the helicopter provides.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pippa has another special connection with the Trust.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,144),('<p>&ldquo;My Dad was a surf lifesaver at Piha for many years starting in the 1960s. I understand the first rescue helicopter service was based out of Piha in the 70s and he would assist with rescues. It&rsquo;s something he&rsquo;s very proud of.&rdquo;<br />\r\n&ldquo;We Kiwis are an adventurous bunch,&rdquo; she tells us, &ldquo;We love to get out and explore our beautiful country and I wholeheartedly encourage that. It does mean though that you can find yourself out of the reach of facilities that you might need should an accident strike &ndash; you never know when you might need them.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pippa&rsquo;s family have never needed to use the service themselves and she hopes they never will.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Every time I see them flying, it gives me pause for thought. You realise there is a family somewhere who is going through significant angst.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pippa&rsquo;s three kids think helicopters are &ldquo;fabulous&rdquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Ambulance helicopters (as they like to call them) are the ultimate though! They&rsquo;re keen to have a close up look, but look, if I&rsquo;m being totally honest, I hope they never have to get too close!&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We hope so too. From our crew to you, thank you Pippa for your generous support.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,144),('<p>Auckland&#39;s only charity yacht regatta - no experience required!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For many years now Trust sponsor Dominion Constructors have partnered with Bassett Plumbing to bring us the Chopper Cup - a unique event where people with no sailing experience get to have a chance at a yachting regatta. Generous yacht owners donate their vessels along with their time to give even the greenest of seafarers a taste of the action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The event takes place in Auckland&#39;s Waitemata Harbour, right out in front of the famous harbour bridge. With 2 classes of vessel available, we offer corporates another &nbsp;opportunity to take part in a truly one of a kind event. Groups of 4-6 or 8-10 have a day out in the beautiful Auckland sun, then join us in the Ponsonby Cruising Club function centre for dinner, drinks and charitable auction.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,166),('<p>If you&#39;ve ever watched yachting from afar or on television and wanted to give it a go, then this is the event for you. Our experienced skippers and first mates guide you through an afternoon&#39;s sailing without you needing to know anything at all.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All registration fees include a day&#39;s sailing for your group, lunch,&nbsp;snacks and drinks on board the boat as well as gourmet BBQ dinner and open bar back at Ponsonby Cruising Club for the after match function. Truly a one of a kind event in the New Zealand charity landscape and one of the most important fundraisers for ARHT every year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The 2017 event will be taking place on Tuesday, November 21st.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>For more information, photos and details on how to register your team visit <a href=\"http://www.choppercup.org.nz\" target=\"_blank\">www.choppercup.org.nz</a></p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,166),('<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/RhQLyNaXoqM\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Catering to both locals and &#39;mainlanders&#39; who love fine food, sunshine and of course wonderful Man O&#39;War wines, this event is a sought after&nbsp;soir&eacute;e on the summer calendar. The event returns again on Sunday, February&nbsp;25th, 2018 (TBC). With the finest food, wine and views this great city can provide, you&#39;ll need to grab your tickets before they sell out. Tickets will be available from October 2017.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the years, New Zealand food royalty have graced our event. We have been blessed to host Josh Emett, Ben Bayly, Sean Connolly, Mark Southon, Gareth Stewart and many, many more elite chefs to present incredible menus for our guests.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a flagship fundraiser for Auckland&#39;s Westpac Rescue Chopper, this event is highly sought after. We provide&nbsp;<span style=\"display: none;\">&nbsp;</span><strong>free</strong> transport (donated by generous sponsor&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.fullers.co.nz/\">Fullers</a>) from Auckland City, via Matiatia, to the private jetty at Man O&#39;War bay - strictly limited to the first 300. Guests enjoy the beautiful lunch and fine wines in a relaxed, garden setting like no other in New Zealand. Live music &amp; a charitable auction feature in a most unique afternoon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thank you to our main event sponsors who help make this wonderful event a reality every year:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/event-photos/neat-meat-logo.jpg\" style=\"width: 90px; height: 90px;\" />&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/event-photos/fullers-logo.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 55px;\" />&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/event-photos/afl1013-moana-logo_cmyk-page-001.jpg\" style=\"width: 194px; height: 100px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>To check out a full gallery of this event, visit the gallery on&nbsp;our&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pg/Rescue1Chopper/photos/?tab=album&amp;album_id=341644885950449\">Facebook page here</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thanks also to&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.sealink.co.nz/waiheke\">Sealink</a>&nbsp;for transporting all of our chefs &amp; their teams to&nbsp;Waiheke&nbsp;for this event. For your next vehicle booking to&nbsp;Waiheke&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/pg/Rescue1Chopper/photos/?tab=album&amp;album_id=341644885950449\">click here</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<!-- Begin MailChimp Signup Form -->\r\n<link href=\"//cdn-images.mailchimp.com/embedcode/classic-10_7.css\" rel=\"stylesheet\" type=\"text/css\" />\r\n<style type=\"text/css\">#mc_embed_signup{background:#fff; clear:left; font:14px Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif; }\r\n</style>\r\n<div id=\"mc_embed_signup\">\r\n<div id=\"mc_embed_signup_scroll\">\r\n<h2>Subscribe for date, chef &amp; ticket announcements!</h2>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"indicates-required\"><span class=\"asterisk\">*</span> indicates required</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"mc-field-group\"><label for=\"mce-EMAIL\">Email Address <span class=\"asterisk\">*</span> </label> <input class=\"required email\" id=\"mce-EMAIL\" name=\"EMAIL\" type=\"email\" value=\"\" /></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"mc-field-group\"><label for=\"mce-FNAME\">First Name <span class=\"asterisk\">*</span> </label> <input class=\"required\" id=\"mce-FNAME\" name=\"FNAME\" type=\"text\" value=\"\" /></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"mc-field-group\"><label for=\"mce-LNAME\">Last Name <span class=\"asterisk\">*</span> </label> <input class=\"required\" id=\"mce-LNAME\" name=\"LNAME\" type=\"text\" value=\"\" /></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"clear\" id=\"mce-responses\">\r\n<div class=\"response\" id=\"mce-error-response\" style=\"display:none\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"response\" id=\"mce-success-response\" style=\"display:none\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- real people should not fill this in and expect good things - do not remove this or risk form bot signups-->\r\n\r\n<div aria-hidden=\"true\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -5000px;\"><input name=\"b_1f6cdf9a4fa8075e1ab4ce527_552b034646\" tabindex=\"-1\" type=\"text\" value=\"\" /></div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"clear\"><input class=\"button\" id=\"mc-embedded-subscribe\" name=\"subscribe\" type=\"submit\" value=\"Subscribe\" /></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<script type=\'text/javascript\' src=\'//s3.amazonaws.com/downloads.mailchimp.com/js/mc-validate.js\'></script><script type=\'text/javascript\'>(function($) {window.fnames = new Array(); window.ftypes = new Array();fnames[0]=\'EMAIL\';ftypes[0]=\'email\';fnames[1]=\'FNAME\';ftypes[1]=\'text\';fnames[2]=\'LNAME\';ftypes[2]=\'text\';fnames[3]=\'MMERGE3\';ftypes[3]=\'text\';}(jQuery));var $mcj = jQuery.noConflict(true);</script><!--End mc_embed_signup-->','col-xs-12',0,1,168),('<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/event-photos/golf-1_0.jpg\" style=\"width: 187px; height: 280px;\" />&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/slideshows/event-slideshow/golf-4.jpg\" style=\"width: 576px; height: 280px;\" />&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/event-photos/golf-3_0.jpg\" style=\"width: 187px; height: 280px;\" /></p>','col-xs-12',0,1,175),('<p>The annual Westpac Rescue golf fundraiser.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For those who like to spoil a good walk by hitting a ball around one of Auckland&#39;s hidden gems - Aviation Country Club. Thanks to our long time supporters,&nbsp;The Pallet Company, who have once again sponsored our annual charity golf day and will no doubt help it be a great success. The event goes from strength to strength each year and teams wishing to play should register early.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This year our annual fundraiser is back and will be taking place on Friday, November 3rd.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,176),('<p>A great way for your company to support the rescue helicopter, and get a great day out on the course at the same time. With games &amp; prizes on course, food and beverage provided along with special celebrity guests, this is your chance to leverage your corporate brand with the rescue chopper. We have a huge array of prizes donated by&nbsp;JK&#39;s&nbsp;World of Golf&nbsp;- adding hugely to the value of the day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dinner and drinks provided at the&nbsp;prizegiving&nbsp;in the clubhouse after the event where we will also have a charitable silent auction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Full teams &amp; individual registrations welcome - contact events manager Nathan by email at <a href=\"mailto:nathant@arht.org.nz\">nathant@arht.org.nz</a></p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,176),('<p>The Auckland based Westpac Rescue Helicopter is staffed full-time by a highly experienced flight crew consisting of pilots, paramedics and crewmen, and operates 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, 365 days a year. In addition to this, the HEMS service complements the team with specialist trauma physicians with the team to make further improvements to the chain of care for the patient.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2010/11 was the Auckland Rescue Helicopter services&rsquo; 40th year in operation.&nbsp; This was a milestone for the service, which started the world&#39;s first ever civilian surf-rescue helicopter service back in late 1970.&nbsp; Since then, the service has performed many thousands of rescues and is internationally recognised for its pioneering work in saving lives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Auckland Rescue Helicopter Trust&#39;s origins date back to the establishment of the Rescue Helicopter Service in 1970. That summer, the Auckland Surf Life Saving Association launched a world first in ocean rescue with the provision of the Hiller 12E helicopter. &nbsp;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,295),('<p>Hiller 12E helicopter. This aircraft was used specifically for rescues from the surf on Auckland&#39;s west coast beaches, and the use of the helicopter for this purpose was a typical demonstration of kiwi ingenuity showing the way!<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn 1990 a Charitable Trust was formed with Trustees selected from the community and business sectors of the greater Auckland region. The primary aim of the Trust is to provide and develop a highly efficient aero medical service for the benefit of the community at large.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h4><strong>International Award</strong></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>ARHT&#39;s outstanding contribution was recognised by the world &quot;Association of Aeromedical Services&quot; in 2000 when we were presented with an award for 10,000 accident free missions.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,295),('<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">For those interested in the details, here are the helicopter specs:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">Aviation Call signs - &quot;Westpac Rescue 1&quot; &amp; &quot;Westpac Rescue 2&quot;</span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">Aircraft Registration -&nbsp;ZK-HLN<span style=\"font-family: inherit;\">&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;</span>ZK-HKZ<span style=\"font-family: inherit;\">,&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>BK117-850<span style=\"font-family: inherit;\">&nbsp;D2 Helicopter&#39;s</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><span style=\"font-family: inherit;\">Single Pilot &amp; Dual Pilot IFR</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">600lb<span style=\"font-family: inherit;\">&nbsp;Breeze Eastern Winch (right hand side&nbsp;fixed mount)</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Radar</strong>&nbsp;(including storm scope)&nbsp;- The Radar enables the pilot to avoid really bad weather which reduces the danger of icing, severe turbulence or lightning strikes.&nbsp; This is particularly important when flying on instruments (IFR) in cloud.&nbsp; The Radar is also a very useful tool in detecting survivors/boats at sea, and when trying to detect or follow coastlines or high ground.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Terrain Avoidance Warning System</strong>&nbsp;(TAWS)&nbsp;- This gives the pilot a map of the height of the terrain in front of the helicopter.&nbsp; If the aircraft descends below a predetermined safe height an alarm sounds in the cockpit.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Traffic Collision Avoidance System</strong>&nbsp;(TCAS).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">A certified&nbsp;<strong>NVIS</strong>&nbsp;(Night Vision Instrument System)&nbsp;in the cockpit for when using Night Vision Goggles.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Nightsun&nbsp;Electronic Flight Indication System</strong>&nbsp;(EFIS).</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Moving Map</strong>&nbsp;- An electronic map which shows all geographic features, airspace boundaries and aircraft tracks.</span></p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-4',0,1,296),('<p><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Horizontal Situation Indicator&nbsp;</strong>(HSI)&nbsp;- Although not a full &ldquo;Glass&rdquo; Cockpit&nbsp;EFIS, one of the central instruments, the compass, and all associated pointers and bearing and distance indicators are on an electronic &lsquo;glass&rsquo; screen.&nbsp; All critical information for the pilot is on one panel right in front of him/her.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"font-size: 13.2px;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Flight following</strong>&nbsp;- This is an electronic device mounted in the aircraft that uses Global Positioning Satellite (GPS) and satellite or cell phone to transmit the helicopters exact location every few seconds to a tracking website.&nbsp; A moving map in can be logged onto which shows the aircraft&rsquo;s position at any time. This means not only&nbsp;ARHT&nbsp;staff can monitor our aircrafts position, but also the Ambulance Control Centre, the Police or the National Rescue Coordination Centre (NRCC) if we are carrying out a Search and Rescue mission.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"font-size: 13.2px;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Emergency beacon tracking Direction Finder</strong>&nbsp;- A state of the art Direction finding device, that allows homing to any emergency beacon; including Marine, air band, military or the latest &lsquo;satellite triggering&rsquo; 406&nbsp;MHz beacons.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"font-size: 13.2px;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>406 MHz Emergency Position Indicating Radio Beacon</strong>&nbsp;(EPIRB)&nbsp;- If we are ever in trouble, our own emergency beacon will be up to the latest standard.&nbsp; Instead of waiting up to 6 hours for a satellite to pick up the exact position of our aircraft, in an emergency the 406 beacons can be tracked in just a few minutes to within a few&nbsp;metres, rather than a few kilometers, as with the old VHF beacons.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"font-size: 13.2px;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong>Satellite Phone</strong>&nbsp;- Allows communication by phone in those areas where cell phone coverage is lost.&nbsp; This is quite common, in the areas we go to.</span></p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-4',0,2,296),('<p style=\"opacity: 1; font-size: 13.2px;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">Additional Information:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"opacity: 1; font-size: 13.2px;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">The Westpac Rescue Helicopter is a totally dedicated rescue aircraft. The interior of the Helicopter is designed for the provision of exceptionally high standards of patient care, maximum efficiency, and the capability to be multi role. The types of rescue missions the Helicopter responds to are many and varied and can be as diverse as sea rescues and car accidents.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"opacity: 1; font-size: 13.2px;\"><br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:14px;\">The Rescue Helicopters standard configuration includes medical, rescue and aviation equipment onboard to ensure that missions are carried out safely to ensure the best patient outcome. The&nbsp;Trust also has further&nbsp;specialised&nbsp;equipment on standby at its&nbsp;Helipad&nbsp;in Mechanics Bay, Auckland.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"opacity: 1; font-size: 13.2px;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\">It is also fitted with multiple stretcher systems, medical oxygen, suction, medical quality lighting, backup power, as well as specialist coronary and neonatal medical equipment, rescue stretchers and rescue diver immersion equipment inside the Helicopter.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"opacity: 1; font-size: 13.2px;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong style=\"opacity: 1;\">Travel Times:</strong><br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\nAuckland -&nbsp;Waiheke&nbsp;Island (9 min)<br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\nAuckland -&nbsp;Piha&nbsp;(15 min)<br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\nAuckland - Great Barrier Island (25 min)<br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\nAuckland -&nbsp;Waiuku&nbsp;(16 min)<br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\nAuckland -&nbsp;Coromandel&nbsp;(35 min)</span><br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"opacity: 1; font-size: 13.2px;\"><span style=\"font-size:14px;\"><strong style=\"opacity: 1;\">Other interesting Facts</strong><br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\nMaximum Speed - 277 kn/h (150 knots)<br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\nCruise Speed - 222 km/h (120 knots)<br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\nMaximum Weight - 3,350 kgs<br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\nFuel&nbsp;Useage&nbsp;- 150&nbsp;litres/hr (per engine)<br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\nNormal Fuel Capacity - 720&nbsp;litres<br style=\"opacity: 1;\" />\r\nNormal Cruising Altitude - 1500 ft</span></p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-4',0,3,296),('<p><strong>WHITIANGA WEATHER</strong>: <a href=\"http://whiti.arht.org.nz/index.php\" target=\"_blank\">http://whiti.arht.org.nz/index.php&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>ARHT Staff Portal</strong>: <a href=\"https://staffportal.arht.org.nz/\" target=\"_blank\">https://staffportal.arht.org.nz/&nbsp;</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>ARHT Email:</strong> <a href=\"https://login.microsoftonline.com/\" target=\"_blank\">https://login.microsoftonline.com/</a></p>','col-xs-12',0,1,308),('<p>The Hirepool Leigh Fishing Contest is our iconic annual fishing event, just an hour north of Auckland in Leigh. It is a great chance for anglers of all ages &amp; experience to visit one of NZ&#39;s friendliest communities all in the name of charity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Leigh Family Fishing Contest has been running for 13 years and is a vital source of community funding for the rescue chopper. With 750 anglers the tournament continues to grow thanks to the likes of our wonderful sponsors<a href=\"http://www.surtees.co.nz/\">&nbsp;Surtees</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.hondamarine.co.nz/\">Honda Marine</a>. Without their amazing first prize of a 4.95m workmate &amp; outboard package this event would not be the same. This year we also welcome Top Catch, Navstation and Okuma to the sponsor family - helping us ensure that this event will be the best yet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>100% of proceeds are donated to the rescue chopper and other Leigh local community causes. In the past 5 years over $200,000 has been raised for these causes thanks to the participation of our wonderful sponsors and generous participants on the day.&nbsp;Make sure you get your tickets for the whole family on March 17th 2018, there is sure to be something for everyone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is over $70,000 worth of cash &amp; prizes up for grabs at this event and all prizes must go. If you&#39;re a keen fisherman you simply must get along and enjoy the weekend.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For tickets and more information visit our great new website thanks to On Fire Design -&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.leighfishingcontest.org.nz\">www.leighfishingcontest.org.nz</a></p>','col-xs-12',0,1,327),('<p>It was 5am in the morning when John Potter snuck out of bed, leaving Pam, his wife and high school crush, to sleep.The retired panel beater, along with his mates Buzz Kronfeld and Oison Frost, enjoyed a day out on the water doing what they loved best &ndash; fishing! As midday approached, with a good catch in hand, the three friends prepared to make the trip home.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The journey would involve crossing the Manukau Bar and on to little Huia on the north side of the harbour &ndash; a trip that John had made multiple times over 20 odd years.&ldquo;There was a swell coming in, but it was fairly gentle,&rdquo; John recalls, &ldquo;Buzz had checked the weather report and the conditions were supposed to be improving.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Any thought of getting into trouble was far from the friends&rsquo; minds. They put in a trip report to Coastguard and proceeded through the entrance.&ldquo;It did seem to roughen up a bit,&rdquo; John recalls, &ldquo;But it was too late to turn back.&rdquo;With just 60 metres to go, disaster struck.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;We were on the back of a large wave when an unexpected second large wave appeared right behind us,&rdquo; John says, &ldquo;The two waves created a massive hole to the right hand side of the boat and we slid sideways into it, while the second wave crashed over us.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The boat rolled twice. John and Oison were in the boat&rsquo;s cockpit at the time. John recalls being flushed out, but he hit his head on the way out and sustained a nasty injury.John thinks Buzz, who was standing at the back of the boat, was washed off first. When he came to the surface, Buzz was clinging to their chilly bin, now empty.Fortunately all three men had their lifejackets on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oison swam his way out of the cockpit and was now holding on to the bow of the upturned boat. He too had suffered a nasty gash to his head.Buzz swam over to John.&ldquo;I told him I was injured bad.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>John and Buzz then swam back to the boat. They managed to get some rope out of the anchor locker, so they had something to hold on to. As the cold set in, they hauled themselves onto the hull of the boat.&ldquo;How I got up there, I don&rsquo;t know,&rdquo; John says, &ldquo;It must have been the adrenaline.&rdquo;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,329),('<p>Waves knocked the men off twice but they held on for some three hours. John could see the boat was starting to drift dangerously southward towards the Awhitu Peninsula.&ldquo;Some big rollers were coming in. They flushed us off the boat a third time and that&rsquo;s when we got separated.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>John was struggling. Bitterly cold, he knew he had to swim to shore away from the boat. He couldn&rsquo;t use his legs but he was fit &ndash; something that would help save his life.&ldquo;I just got on my back and started paddling with my arms.&rdquo; John found himself at the mercy of three massive waves as he made his way slowly to shore. &ldquo;After the third one, I could feel firm ground beneath me. I just crawled out and made my way up onto dry land.&rdquo;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the meantime, Buzz and Oison had managed to swim to shore. The waves had carried them 400-500 metres further down the harbour. The two men looked for their skipper but he was nowhere to be seen. Buzz raced up the hill to a nearby property where, fortunately, both a park ranger and volunteer from the fire brigade happened to be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Coming down on quadbikes, they found me,&rdquo; John recalls, &ldquo;The rescue helicopter was called in to help.&rdquo;Westpac 1 was involved in the initial search which involved three helicopters and boats, the police and Coastguard. After being diverted to a critical mission in Piha, Westpac 1 returned. The crew transported John, in a serious condition, to Auckland Hospital. This took less than 30 minutes from locating him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>John was in hospital for three weeks. He returned home for Christmas, where he spent a further six weeks recovering on his back.&ldquo;My pelvis was split open,&rdquo; John says, &ldquo;they call it an open book break. They put a titanium plate in.&rdquo; John also received 18 staples for the wound on his head.&ldquo;He&rsquo;s like the Mechano Man!&rdquo; Pam says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>John is slowly recovering. He hits the gym three days a week and attends ongoing physio sessions.Pam says the rescue helicopter often flies over their home in West Auckland on the way to rescues out on the West Coast. John and Pam were already big supporters through the family business, but now the service has more significance than ever.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>John still enjoys his fishing. He bought exactly the same boat. Pam says one lesson he&rsquo;s learnt from the experience is never to leave without saying goodbye again!</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,329),('<p>We know there are many people out there in the community who are DOERS and like to get out there and raise money on our behalf.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are many ways to go about this, and we love to hear from those of you that are getting out there and raising money for our cause.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whether you&#39;re undertaking a major challenge or simply hosting a local event, don&#39;t hesitate to drop us a line to let us know what you&#39;re doing.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-4',0,1,340),('<p>Unfortunately we don&#39;t have a specific fundraising campaign just yet (we&#39;re working on it!), but by the end of 2017 we will be a special fundraising activity for individuals, schools or businesses to undertake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Keep a look out for the re-vamped &#39;Chopper Challenge&#39; as we get later in the year. If you&#39;re not signed up to get updates from us, you can do so at the bottom of the page - just pop in your email address and you&#39;ll begin receiving our monthly Chopper Chats.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-4',0,2,340),('<p>If you&#39;re already participating in an event or want to do some fundraising for us on your own, then head over to our fundraising platform here:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://nfp.everydayhero.com/nz/auckland-rescue-helicopter\" target=\"_blank\">https://nfp.everydayhero.com/nz/auckland-rescue-helicopter</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&acirc;&euro;&lsaquo;Then you can setup a page, target and mission and get out there to start fundraising!</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-4',0,3,340),('<p><iframe allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"315\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/qXHinT07GkM\" width=\"560\"></iframe></p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,348),('<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To save one life, the Auckland &amp;&nbsp;Coromandel&nbsp;Westpac Rescue Helicopter needs $4,500 of community funding. Alone, it may seem like a lot, but when people come together to sponsor a mission, it costs very little to save one life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why not become a Mission Sponsor?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From as little as $25 a month, you along with&nbsp;fourteen other kind-hearted Kiwis can help save the life of one person.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a Mission Sponsor, you have the opportunity to get a group of fifteen together, or we&#39;ll match you with like-minded individuals from your community.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,348),('<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On receipt of your first monthly payment of $25 a month or more, you will receive a special certificate detailing the mission you have helped sponsor with a thank you letter from a crew member involved with your mission.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where possible, one of the crew will be in touch to let you know how the patient is doing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a Mission Sponsor you will also be invited to an Open Day where you can see the crew in action and meet other Mission Sponsors just like you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you get a group of fifteen people together, the crew will meet you&nbsp;at base.&nbsp;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,349),('<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/slideshows/home-page-slider/slider-1.jpg\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 281px;\" /></p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,349),('<p>To save one life, the Auckland &amp; Coromandel Westpac Rescue Helicopter needs $4,500 of community funding. Alone, it may seem like a lot, but when people come together to sponsor a mission, it costs very little to save one life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why not become a Mission Sponsor?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From as little as $25 a month, you along with fourteen other kind-hearted Kiwis can help save the life of one person.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a Mission Sponsor, you have the opportunity to get a group of fifteen together, or we&#39;ll match you with like-minded individuals from your community.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,350),('<p>On receipt of your first monthly payment of $25 a month or more, you will receive a special certificate detailing the mission you have helped sponsor with a thank you letter from a crew member involved with your mission.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where possible, one of the crew will be in touch to let you know how the patient is doing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a Mission Sponsor you will also be invited to an Open Day where you can see the crew in action and meet other Mission Sponsors just like you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you get a group of fifteen people together, the crew will come to meet you all, either at base or we&#39;ll come to you. Conditions apply - refer below.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,350),('<p>Lorem Ipsum&nbsp;is simply dummy text of the printing and typesetting industry. Lorem Ipsum has been the industry&#39;s standard dummy text ever since the 1500s, when an unknown printer took a galley of type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,353),('<p>Lorem Ipsum&nbsp;is simply dummy text of the printing and typesetting industry. Lorem Ipsum has been the industry&#39;s standard dummy text ever since the 1500s, when an unknown printer took a galley of type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,353),('<p><strong>What is a bequest?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A bequest is a &#39;future&#39; charitable donation. It is a method of supporting the work of the Auckland Westpac Rescue Helicopters without it affecting your lifestyle today. Simply put, it is a charitable gift left in your Will.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>How do I leave&nbsp;a bequest?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Leaving a bequest is a simple process that your solicitor can implement for you. Once you have provided in your Will for your loved ones, your solicitor can add a gift to our service. If you already have a Will and just want to update it, your solicitor can provide a Codicil document for this purpose, which you will need to date and sign. To see the wording to give to your solicitor to update your Will,&nbsp;<a href=\"/library/bequest-page/become-a-supporter-for-life-info-for-lawyer.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">CLICK HERE</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What will the money be spent on?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Money received from bequests is used towards the purchase of capital items, such as emergency medical equipment for the team to use on board the helicopter. Currently however, we are saving up for a new up-to-date replacement helicopter, as our two machines are over 25 years old.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-4',0,1,354),('<p><strong>What benefit is there&nbsp;for me to leave a charitable bequest?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a number of benefits in relation to leaving a gift in your Will. The first and most important one is the knowledge that your gift is long-lasting and will ensure the survival of our service for future generations. It will mean that we can continue to operate two helicopters in the Auckland,&nbsp;Coromandel&nbsp;and Rodney regions, 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, enabling us to attend more than 1,000 rescue missions each year. Your&nbsp;gift <u>will be</u> saving lives. To download our bequest brochure,&nbsp;<a href=\"/library/bequest-page/bequest-brochure.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">CLICK HERE</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another benefit reported by our&nbsp;bequestors&nbsp;is the &quot;feel good&quot; factor. It is an amazing feeling to do something so selfless as to leave a legacy not only for your own family, but for countless other families too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The wonderful thing about the service we provide is that it is not restricted or specific. We rescue people of all nationalities, ages, genders or religions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And thirdly, by leaving a bequest you will automatically be welcomed into our Supporter for Life program.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-4',0,2,354),('<p><strong>What is the Supporter for Life program?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>By leaving a bequest, you will automatically be welcomed into our Supporter for Life (SFL) legacy program. You will receive a welcome pack, a badge to wear with pride, and get invited to our annual Christmas morning tea at the helicopter base. You will receive a quarterly update of what has been happening with our service and get invited to other events throughout the year. The Supporter for Life program is our way of&nbsp;thanking you&nbsp;for your future support of us.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/bequest-page/sfl_red-logo.jpg\" style=\"width: 106px; height: 72px;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>If you would like to know more, please call:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kerrie Spicer<img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/kez.jpg\" style=\"width: 127px; height: 129px; float: right;\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Planned Giving Manager</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ph: (09) 950 7222</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mobile: 021 2748458</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Email: <a href=\"mailto:bequests@arht.org.nz\">bequests@arht.org.nz</a></p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-4',0,3,354),('<h1 style=\"text-align: center;\">Testimonials from our Supporter for Life members</h1>','col-xs-12',0,1,355),('<h1 style=\"text-align: right;\"><a id=\"Jo\" name=\"Jo\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/bequest-page/jo-underwood.jpg\" style=\"width: 141px; height: 198px; float: left;\" /></a>Jo Underwood, Waiheke</h1>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">Supporter for Life, Regular Supporter, Ex-Patient</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">In September 2016, Jo began to feel ill, suffering symptoms similar to a mini-stroke. Intensive Care Paramedic, Bruce Kerr, was on-board the helicopter that day and the crew flew Jo to Auckland City Hospital in a serious condition.</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,356),('<p>&quot;I was already a regular supporter and had also left a gift to the service in my Will, and now I am so glad I did. It&#39;s a service I have always believed in and one you know is going to save an awful lot of lives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Leaving a gift&nbsp; was an easy and simple process and something I would encourage others to do if they want the helicopter to be around in the future.&quot;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,356),('<h1 style=\"text-align: right;\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/library/bequest-page/stewart-rundle.jpg\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 167px; float: left;\" />Stewart Rundle, Castor Bay</h1>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">Support for Life, Regular Supporter, Ex-Patient</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align: right;\">In January 2015, Stewart Rundle fell 30 metres down a cliff and lived to tell the tale.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,1,357),('<p>&quot;My decision to leave a gift in my Will was a way in which I could feel in control of my own destiny and one where I could also help others. It was a simple decision to make. You never think you are going to need rescuing and certainly not by helicopter, but when you need one - you really need one!&quot;</p>','col-xs-12 col-sm-6 col-md-6',0,2,357);
